featured_reviews.review_id:
The construction of this mosque was completed in 1262 A.H/1845 C.E.The famous Cutchi Memon 'Noorani family'of Mumbai contributed significantly towards the construction of this mosque.The exquisitely carved wooden pillars of the mosque were brought from Mumbai in Patemar(cabotage vessel).The graves of 8 members of the Noorani family are found in the mosque graveyard.The tombstones give dates ranging from 1841 to 1876 C.E.
For the maintenance of this mosque,the Nooranis bequeathed landed properties in Alappuzha and earmarked a sum of Rs. 300 annually from their Trust in Bombay.The document registered with the Charity Commissioner of Maharashtra in Mumbai states, "Rs. 300/- per year for the upkeep of the Masjid at Alpada".This amount is received from Mumbai every year.
The friday khutba (sermon) in this mosque was delivered in urdu till 1988 C.E,when it was switched over to Malayalam.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Known also as the Eastern Shafi Juma Masjid ,this mosque is named after a sufi saint Abdullah Masthan.Built in typical Kerala style,this mosque is nearly 250 years old.Its architecture is strikingly similar to that of the old mosques of Thalassery.The  mosque has rich wooden interiors.It has an ablution pond very much similar to those found in Hindu temples.The mosque has in its premises,  the shrine of Abdullah Masthan.
It functioned as the central mosque of the town, before other mosques were established in Alappuzha.For decades, the mosque administration was controlled by caretakers appointed by the Travancore Maharaja.The Maharaja granted these caretakers (Mutawallis) the status of a Magistrate.A Yemeni scholar Abu Yafee was the chief imam of the mosque nearly 200 years back.The Madrasthul Muhammadiyya and Hashimiyya Madrasa which functioned under this mosque had at one time,teachers from as far as Egypt.

featured_reviews.review_id: Quaint little mosque with unique double minarets, stained glass windows, an ornate prayer niche (mihrab) and chandeliers. It was originally built in the 1850s as a thatched-roof prayer mosque (Taikka palli) for travelers who visited the town of Alleppey. The Halai Memons (from the Halar region of Kathiawar, Gujarat) who were involved in the trade of hill-produce, played a major role in the establishment of the mosque. The mosque is believed to take its name from a Tamil mendicant named Shaukar, who inaugurated the mosque. It was later renovated on the 17th Vrischikam 1109 Malayalam era (December 2, 1933) under the leadership of Athukka Haji- a wholesale rice merchant. The mosque was refurbished as part of the Alappuzha Heritage Project of Government of Kerala and opened for worship on November 3, 2020.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Saukar masjid

The Halayi Momens, who migrated from Gujarat, erected the 250-year-old Saukar Masjid, which is one of Alappuzha's oldest mosques. The masjid was conserved as a part of the Alappuzha Heritage Project. The Muslims of the Halayi Momen community used to frequent to Kerala for business, during the reign of Dharma Raja Karthika Thirunal. The mosque was built on a plot of land that was granted to them by Raja Keshavadas, the Diwan of Travancore. The architecture of the mosque exhibits characteristics from Turkish or Eastern European styles. The roof along with the original structure was restored to its former glory. The restoration aims to preserve the rich history and heritage of the place. The conservation of the Saukar Masjid helped in the upliftment of the entire neighbourhood, and the cleaning of the water canals.
